postcontent:
Up for sale is a completely custom Remington 700p LTR.  This rifle is outfitted with multiple high end upgrades from JP Rifles, LaRue Tactical, Harris, and Kahntrol.  This rifle is was recently finished.  It was originally going to be my personal long range rifle but I need the cash.  It has not been fired in it's current build.  Please contact me with any questions you may have.

I am asking for $3,250.  Please take into account that JP Rifles sells their AMCS Rifle without the upgrades for $4k.  It is not a 20" LTR Barrel and it does not come with three 10 round magazines or the Harris Bipod.  This rifle will include the original Rem 700p LTR Stock and a hard carry case.

I am willing to ship this rifle to an FFL after payment has been made.  Details on the rifle are listed below:

The Build

I.  Remington 700P Light Tactical Rifle, LTR
	-Caliber:  .308 WIN
	-Barrel Length:  20" (Fluted)
	-Standard Twist:  12"
II.  Larue Tactical Remington 700 MIL-STD-1913 Picatinny Rail with built in 20 MOA
III.  Kahntrol Clamp On Muzzle Break
IV.  Harris Bipod, 6-9" Leg Notch Swivel Version
V.  JP Enterprises' Advanced Modular Chassis System (AMCS) with three 10 Round Magazines

Remington 700p LTR

Model 700P LTR (Light Tactical Rifle), chambered for .308 Win.; features a slimmed down stock to improve portability and reduce weight. The flutes in the 20" LTR not only assist in weight reduction and heat dissipation, but are engineered to enhance barrel rigidity for pinpoint accuracy.

Like its big brother, the LTR stock is laid up around an aircraft-grade aluminum bedding block that runs up the entire length of the receiver. It has a textured, black, non-reflective finish and comes with sling swivel studs.

 JP Advanced Modular Chassis System™

The JP AMCS™ is the direct result of years of long-range shooting experience. After trying another aftermarket chassis, I realized that I wanted the vastly superior ergonomics of a gas-operated rifle such as the AR-15/AR-10 platforms for my bolt gun. The JP chassis delivers the best of all worlds. The cheek piece can be raised to accommodate an AR-15-type optics mounting system like the JPFTSM-30 with the line of bore relative to shoulder identical to the gas gun. Combined with the palm shelf grip, you have the most comfortable chassis system with the most linear impulse feel and reduced muzzle rise possible. For a more traditional bolt gun setup, you need only lower the cheek piece and use your preferred standard height rings.

The JP AMCS™ is completely machined from 6061 T6 aircraft-grade aluminum with the mil-standard black hard coat anodizing process. The chassis will accept any Remington 700 right-hand short action or clone thereof as well as Savage short action rifles. The ambidextrous, extended magazine release does not require the operator to relinquish the shooting grip to perform a magazine change. The chassis includes the precision type tactical grip with palm shelf, fully adjustable folding butt stock, QD studs for bipod or sling systems and is also designed to accept the Accu-Shot Monopod system. We sell JP magazines that will hold 10 rounds of any cartridge based on the 308 Winchester with an OAL of 2.820 or less. The JP magazine can also feed 7 rounds of short mag with slight modification.

postcontent:
Guns of Liberty Trading
Sales, Service, Trading and Transfers 
www.gunsoflibertytrading.com

Specifications:
Manufacturer: Kel-Tec
Model: 12 Gauge 3”
Caliber: KSG
Capacity: 6+6+1
Method of Operation: Pump
Overall Length 26.1 inches
Barrel Length: 18.5 inches
Weight: 6.9 lbs, 8.5 lbs
Condition: Used

Product Details:
The KSG (Kel-Tec Shotgun) is Kel-Tec CNC’s first entry into the shotgun market. The size, shape, and design is similar to the currently available Kel-Tec RFB rifle, but the KSG ejects downward, instead of forward. The KSG weighs 6.9 lbs. and is as compact as legally possible with a 26.1” overall length and an 18.5” cylinder bore barrel. Even with this compact size, the internal dual tube magazines hold an impressive 12 rounds of 12 gauge 3” rounds in total (6 per tube). It can also reliably shoot shells as short as 1 3/4" up to the 3".

This simple and reliable pump action feeds from either the left or right tube. The feed side is manually selected by a lever located behind the trigger guard.

The pump includes an under picatinny rail for the mounting of a forward grip, a light, or a laser. The included top picatinny sight rail will accept many types of optics or iron sights. Forward and rear sling loops are built in, and a basic sling is included. The soft rubber butt pad helps to tame recoil.

The KSG receiver is made from hardened steel and includes the magazine tubes which have been welded in place. The grip and stock assembly is made of glass reinforced nylon (Zytel) and is easily disassembled by pushing out 2 pins, which store in 2 holes in the grip when removed. The barrel and pump assembly is removed by loosening the 2 front magazine tube nuts with a coin and sliding the assembly forward.

Extra:
Includes MBUS Front and Rear Sight
Includes Surefire Z70 Picatinny Rail Covers

Zytel (Glass Reinforced Nylon) Grip and Stock

Easy Disassembly

title: For Sale:  Ammunition for Sale
postcontent:
Just wanted to give everyone selling ammo a heads up. 

I know for a fact that the dramatic increase in private ammunition sales has concerned many city officials in Ohio and Michigan. I've personally taken call after call from citizens complaining about people making ammo transactions on public and private property. There have been more than a few incidents of private people selling to people with firearm disabilities (under age, felony conviction, etc). I guarantee those people will be made examples of just to further someone's political career. 

Know the law and ask the buyer the appropriate questions. Ask to see their ID to check they're age. If the buyer "just doesn't seem right", don't sell to them. I know for an absolute fact that local, state and federal law enforcement keeps a close eye on Armslist. People repeatedly selling large quantities have already been targeted. They will definitely be tested and probably already are. If you're consistently selling ammo you better be collecting local and state sales tax and declaring to the IRS because that's their fallback plan. They'll get any way they can.

Google anonymous email and learn about it. 

Armslist allows you to see everything a single buyer has for sale. Makes it very easy to see who selling for profit. If you're selling large quantities, use as many Armslist accounts as you can and make sure to use different IP addresses when you setup and access them. If you haven't done this already and have more than a box or two of ammo for sale, then you're on law enforcement's  radar.

Research the buyer. Check the header info when you receive an email. Google their email address - if it comes up with zero hits it's probably new. Not a good sign. 

I hope this was helpful.
